SIMPLE: conscript
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Conscript
<hw>Con"script</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>conscriptus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>conscribere</ets> to write
together, to enroll; <ets>con-</ets> + <ets>scribere</ets> to write. See
<er>Scribe</er>.]</ety> <def>Enrolled; written; registered.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Conscript fathers</b></col> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld>,
<cd>the senators of ancient Rome. When certain new senators were first
enrolled with the ⟦ldquo⟧fathers⟦rdquo⟧ the body was called <xex>Patres
et Conscripti</xex>; afterward all were called <xex>Patres
conscripti</xex>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Conscript</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Conscript
<hw>Con"script</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One taken by lot, or
compulsorily enrolled, to serve as a soldier or sailor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Conscript</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Conscript
<hw>Con*script"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To enroll, by
compulsion, for military service.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Conscription</ent>⟦br⟧
